{{spanish name 2|S<U+00E1>nchez|M<U+00E1>rquez}}
'''Hugo S<U+00E1>nchez M<U+00E1>rquez''' (July 11, 1958), popularly  nicknamed '''''Pentapichichi''''', or '''''Hugol''''', is a [[Mexico|Mexican]] [[Association football|football]] [[coach (sport)|coach]] and former [[striker]]. He played for four European [[football club|clubs]], including [[Real Madrid]]. Sanchez is considered the first highly talented Mexican player. He was also a member of the [[Mexico national football team|Mexico national team]], and participated in three [[FIFA World Cup|World Cups]].


As a coach, he won two championships as head coach of the club [[Pumas de la UNAM]] and briefly with [[Club Necaxa]], both teams in the [[Primera Divisi<U+00F3>n de M<U+00E9>xico|Mexican Primera Divisi<U+00F3>n]]. He also had a sixteen-month stint with the [[Mexico national football team|Mexican national team]], but was fired on [[March 31|March 31, 2008]].<ref>{{Cite document |last= |first= |title=Hugo Sanchez fired as coach of Mexico|url=http://www.iht.com/articles/ap/2008/03/31/sports/SOC-Mexico-Sanchez-Fired.php|accessdate=2008-03-31 |publisher= [[International Herald Tribune]] |postscript= <!--None-->}}</ref> Hugo Sanchez has signed up to start coaching again, now in Europe, for [[UD Almer<U+00ED>a]] [http://www.udalmeriasad.com/udalmeria/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=1773&Itemid=59] from the Spanish First Division starting December 29, in an attempt to save the team from descending to the 2nd Division by the Summer. He has succeeded in keeping [[UD Almeria]] free from relegation from [[La Liga]] for the 2009-2010 season.

In 1999, the [[IFFHS]] voted him the 26th best [[football(soccer)|footballer]] of the 20th Century, and the best [[football (soccer)|footballer]] from the [[CONCACAF]] region.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/iffhs-century.html#cnpoy | author=Stokkermans, Karel | publisher=[[RSSSF]] | title=IFFHS' Century Elections | accessdate=2006-12-17}}</ref>

== Early career ==
As a teenager, S<U+00E1>nchez played for the [[Mexico national football team]] in the [[1976 Summer Olympics]]. Having already played in over 80 international games, S<U+00E1>nchez signed as a youth player at the age of 18 for [[UNAM Pumas]], a professional team representing Mexico's National University, where he completed a degree in Dentistry while keeping up his football career. That year, UNAM managed to get its first championship in the [[Primera Divisi<U+00F3>n de M<U+00E9>xico|Mexican Football League]]. Two years later, he became top-scorer in the league with 26 goals. In 1979, UNAM agreed to exchange players during the off-seasons with the [[San Diego Sockers (NASL)|San Diego Sockers]] of the [[North American Soccer League]] (NASL). The NASL played during the summer and the Mexican League played during the fall, winter and spring. UNAM loaned S<U+00E1>nchez to the Sockers in both 1979 and 1980 where he became a dominant striker for the Sockers, averaging nearly a goal a game.

S<U+00E1>nchez' five seasons with UNAM were the team's golden years. In his last season with the team, Hugo and UNAM won its second championship and the [[CONCACAF Champions Cup]].

==Career ==
<!-- Unsourced image removed: [[Image:Hugosanchez1.jpg|thumb|left|Hugo S<U+00E1>nchez.]] -->
After five successful seasons in Mexico, with 99 goals to his name, S<U+00E1>nchez drew the attention of several Spanish sides, and signed with [[Atl<U+00E9>tico Madrid]] in 1981. He turned down an offer to play for [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal FC]]. {{Citation needed|date=May 2011}} It took him a while to find his feet in [[La Liga]], but by the 1984-85 season he was scoring regularly with a team that won the [[Copa del Rey]], finished in second place in the [[Spanish League]] and won the [[Spanish Super Copa]]. That year Hugo also won his first [[Pichichi trophy]] for being the most prolific scorer in the league.

At the high-point of his career, he signed for [[Real Madrid]] in 1985 and played with players such as [[Jos<U+00E9> Antonio Camacho|Camacho]], [[Emilio Butrague<U+00F1>o|Butrague<U+00F1>o]], [[Rafael Gordillo|Gordillo]], [[Bernd Schuster|Schuster]], [[Jorge Valdano|Valdano]] and [[Jos<U+00E9> Miguel Gonz<U+00E1>lez Mart<U+00ED>n|M<U+00ED>chel]]. This team won five consecutive league titles (from 1985-86 to 1989-90), the ''Copa del Rey'' in 1989, and the [[UEFA Cup]] in 1986. During those five years, S<U+00E1>nchez garnered four consecutive Pichichi trophies (the only player in Spain's football history to achieve this without sharing the trophy on any season), scoring 207 goals in 283 games. He scored 27 or more goals in four consecutive seasons between 1986 and 1990, including 38 goals in the 1989-90 season, tying the single-season record set in 1951 by [[Telmo Zarra]] and earning the [[European Golden Boot]] award to the best scorer in Europe. Overall, he scored 47 goals in 45 European Cup games.

In 1992, S<U+00E1>nchez returned to his native Mexico for a season, before playing for a variety of clubs in Spain, [[Austria]] and the USA (he played for the [[FC Dallas|Dallas Burn]] in the inaugural year of [[Major League Soccer]], becoming one of two people, along with [[Roy Wegerle]], to play outdoor football in both the [[North American Soccer League|NASL]] and [[Major League Soccer|MLS]]). He finished his career playing for [[Atl<U+00E9>tico Celaya]] with Butrague<U+00F1>o and M<U+00ED>chel, his old colleagues from Real Madrid.

==International career==
In comparison to his "domestic" club success, S<U+00E1>nchez did not have a successful international career with the Mexican national team. He played 60 matches and scored 29 goals for the [[Mexico national football team|Mexican national team]], but his years as a Mexican international coincided with a difficult period for the nation's football. Mexico did not participate in the [[FIFA World Cup|World Cup]] of [[1982 World Cup|1982]] and [[1990 World Cup|1990]], in which S<U+00E1>nchez would have most likely been part of the Mexican squad. He scored one goal in eight appearances in the three World Cups in which he competed and was never selected for the [[FIFA World Cup awards#All-Star Team|"Best XI"]] World Cup squads. S<U+00E1>nchez's brash personality is often cited as the reason he did not play many games at the 1994 World Cup, purportedly as a result of internecine frictions between Hugo and the [[Federaci<U+00F3>n Mexicana de F<U+00FA>tbol Asociaci<U+00F3>n|Mexican Football Federation (FMF)]].{{citation needed|date=January 2007}}

