== Retirement ==
S<U+00E1>nchez retired from Spanish football on May 29, 1997, playing with Real Madrid at the [[Santiago Bernab<U+00E9>u stadium]]<U+2014>the stadium that witnessed most of his glory throughout his career. His last official game was in the 1998 World Cup preliminaries where he just touched the ball as a symbol of his retirement.

=== Legacy ===
His trademark was to perform a celebratory somersault after each goal he scored, honoring his sister, who was a gymnast and participated in the Montreal Olympics.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.univision.com/content/content.jhtml?cid=719108|author=Andal<U+00F3>, Paula |title=Hugo S<U+00E1>nchez, con alas en los pies|publisher=Univision|accessdate=2007-07-04|language=Spanish}}</ref> He is also known for acrobatic goals, some involving his trademark windmill kick, a product of his own early training in gymnastics.{{citation needed|date=January 2007}} To date, he has been the most successful Mexican football player by far to have played anywhere, in terms of years played, goalscoring, and achievements.

