== Honours as a player==
=== National championships ===
* 2 [[Primera Divisi<U+00F3>n de M<U+00E9>xico]] ([[Club Universidad Nacional|UNAM]], as player, seasons 1976-77 and 1980<U+2013>81).
* 5 [[La Liga]] ([[Real Madrid]], seasons 1985-86, 1986<U+2013>87, 1987<U+2013>88, 1988<U+2013>89 and 1989<U+2013>90).
* 2 [[Copa del Rey|Copas del Rey]] ([[Atl<U+00E9>tico Madrid]] 1985; [[Real Madrid]] 1989).
* 4 [[Supercopa de Espa<U+00F1>a|Supercopas de Espa<U+00F1>a]] ([[Atl<U+00E9>tico Madrid]] 1985; [[Real Madrid]] 1988, 1989 and 1990).

=== International cups ===
* 1 [[UEFA Cup]] ([[Real Madrid]], season 1985-86).
* 2 [[CONCACAF Champions' Cup]] ([[Club Universidad Nacional|UNAM]] 1980, [[Club Am<U+00E9>rica]] 1992).
* 1 [[Copa Interamericana]] ([[Club Universidad Nacional|UNAM]] 1981).
* 1 [[CONCACAF Gold Cup]] ([[Mexico national football team]] 1977).

=== Individual honours ===
* 1 [[European Golden Boot]] (season 1989-90).
* 5 [[Pichichi Trophy|Pichichis]] (1985, 1986, 1987, 1988 and 1990 with Atletico Madrid and Real Madrid).
* Top scorer of the [[Primera Divisi<U+00F3>n de M<U+00E9>xico|Mexican League]] (1978).
* 2 times Don Balon Award, for being the best foreign player in the  [[La Liga|Spanish League]] (1987 and 1990).
* Best [[Sport]]ist of [[Mexico]] of the 20th century.
* Best [[Association football|footballer]] of [[Mexico]] of the 20th century according to [[International Federation of Football History & Statistics|IFFHS]].
* Best [[Association football|footballer]] of [[North America]] and [[Central America]] of the 20th century by [[International Federation of Football History & Statistics|IFFHS]].
* Only Mexican who appeared in [[Pel<U+00E9>]]'s [[FIFA 100|125 Top Living Football Players List]] in March 2004.
* La Liga Best Replacement Manager 2008-2009.

== Honours as a Coach==
* 2 [[Primera Divisi<U+00F3>n de M<U+00E9>xico]] ([[Club Universidad Nacional|UNAM]] Clausura 2004 and Apertura 2004).
* 1 [[Trofeo Santiago Bernab<U+00E9>u]] ([[Club Universidad Nacional|UNAM]]).

== Personal life ==
S<U+00E1>nchez is the son of H<U+00E9>ctor S<U+00E1>nchez, who played for ''Asturias'' and [[Atlante F.C.|Atlante]]. Hugo S<U+00E1>nchez is married to Isabel Mart<U+00ED>n and has two children, a son and an older daughter from his previous marriage. His son, [[Hugo S<U+00E1>nchez Portugal]] was a football player and has played in [[UNAM Pumas]] like him.

S<U+00E1>nchez was appointed as the official FIFA/SOS Ambassador for Mexico, joining [[Wayne Rooney]] (Ambassador for England), [[Ruud van Nistelrooy]] (Netherlands), and fifty others in fund raising for the official [[2006 FIFA World Cup]] Charity.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sos-childrensvillages.org/news-and-media/news/pages/sanchez-calls-on-football-fans-to-support-sos-childrens-villages.aspx | publisher=[[SOS Children's Villages]] | title=Hugo S<U+00E1>nchez to attend 6 villages for 2006 opening in Morelia| accessdate=2008-08-06}}</ref>

On September 1, 2007 Hugo Sanchez inaugurated a street with his name in Puebla, central Mexico, before a thousand of the locals around there.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.elpais.com/articulo/deportes/Inaugurada/Mexico/calle/Hugo/Sanchez/elpepudep/20070901elpepudep_1/Tes | author= | publisher=[[El Pais]] | title=Inaugurada en M<U+00E9>xico la calle Hugo S<U+00E1>nchez| accessdate=2007-09-01}}</ref>

